      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "# The Lay of the Land: Toronto Maple Leafs\n\nThe Maple Leafs' season didn't end with a bang - it ended with a whimper, a seven-game losing streak that felt less like a collapse and more like an inevitability. At 32-36-14, Toronto finished eighth in the Atlantic Division, 31 games behind the pace-setters, their 78 points a damning indictment of a roster that promised more. <strong>The team won the NHL Draft Lottery yesterday, securing the first overall pick</strong> - a small mercy for a front office facing serious questions about construction and continuity. The lottery gods rewarded failure, as they do, but McKenna or Stenberg at No. 1 won't fix what ails this roster. The real reckoning begins now: coaching scrutiny, free agency decisions, and a hard look at whether this core can be salvaged or whether a genuine rebuild is the only honest path forward. <strong>Watch for management's draft strategy and any early offseason moves - they'll reveal whether the Leafs are tinkering around the edges or admitting the experiment needs overhauling.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated May 6, 2026"
      },
