      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The Blue Jays are drowning. Nine games below.500, nine games out of first place, and now staring at a three-game losing streak that feels less like a rough patch and more like a reckoning. They came to Tampa needing answers. They left with more questions. <strong>The Rays walked them off yesterday, 4-3, scratching out two eighth-inning runs after Kazuma Okamoto had given Toronto an early lead with his tenth home run of the season.</strong> A rookie's power can't save a team that can't hold leads - and won't hold a playoff spot if this continues. At 16-20, third in the AL East, the Jays are already staring at a 12-seed ceiling, a postseason afterthought if they limp in at all. Okamoto's bat is alive - 23 RBIs already - but one hot prospect doesn't carry a franchise out of a hole this deep. The bullpen has become a turnstile. The defense keeps finding new ways to break. <strong>They face Tampa again today at 12:10 PM ET, a chance to salvage something from this wreck before it gets worse.</strong> This is the moment. Lose again, and the season's trajectory shifts from concerning to critical.",
        "updated": "Updated May 6, 2026"
      },
